 half of the twentieth century, due to efforts by political scientists, psychologists, sociologists, economists, philosophers, mathematicians, and geographers who contributed to "social power literature." Baldwin brings the insights of this literature to bear on the three principal theoretical traditions in international relations theory. He discusses controversial issues in power analysis, and shows the relevance of older works frequently underappreciated today.Focusing on the social power perspective in international relations, this book sheds light on how power has been considered during the last half century and how it should be approached in future research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aInternational relations. 0aPower (Social sciences) 0aPower (Social sciences). 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh  aArnold Wolfers.  aErnst Haas.  aFrederick Sherwood Dunn.  aHans J. Morgenthau.  aHarold Sprout.  aJoseph S. Nye Jr.  aMargaret Sprout.  aPower and Interdependence.  aQuincy Wright.  aRichard Snyder.  aRobert Dahl.  aRobert O. Keohane.  aconstructivism.  acounterfactual conditions.  aculture.  aessential contestability.  afungibility.  ainternational relations literature.  ainternational relations theory.  ainternational relations.  amaterialism.  amilitary power.  aneoliberalism.  aneorealism.  aoffensive realism.  apolitical science.  apower analysis.  apower.  aproperty concepts.  arealism.  arelational concepts.  asocial power.  asoft power.  azero-sum power.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311063859240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400881000zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400881000423